{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e462534-28c6-4a75-a919-9f7237433d01","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead — it's more precise and doesn't risk passing if the wrong line throws:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call\n- You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e59c6cb-c4c4-46a0-a89d-0d38bc576cc4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"0BD8:38E18D:3BF493:45DBB8:69F00CCE"},"id":"4bbb5185-610b-4dc0-8a6c-b355ac06985c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:26:44.578Z","parentId":"e10d94d8-0c06-463a-b372-87f8b07484de"}
